# Gemini OpenAI Adapter project rules

- Respond to the user in Chinese by default.
- The repository root is the folder containing `openai_adapter_server.py`, `pyproject.toml`, and `.git`. Do not assume it is named `Gemini-API`; cloned folders may be named `gemini-openai-adapter` or another local name.
- This machine uses Windows PowerShell. Do not use `&&`; use `;` or separate command calls. Prefer `Set-Location (git rev-parse --show-toplevel); command` when already somewhere inside the repo.
- Check PowerShell command success with `$LASTEXITCODE`. Do not claim success if visible output contains `fatal:`, `ParserError`, `InvalidEndOfLine`, or `^C`.
- Treat the upstream Gemini-API core as read-only unless the user explicitly asks otherwise. Prefer adapter changes in `openai_adapter_server.py` and adapter helper files.
- Keep Gemini adapter prompt input within the practical 32k-token working budget. The adapter hard stop is 48k tokens, and the local probe found about 64k tokens can succeed but 128k fails.
- Do not intentionally read or send full-project context, huge logs, generated files, caches, or repeated file contents when the task can be solved with targeted file reads.
- For tasks that may exceed 32k prompt tokens, split the work into smaller phases, summarize findings, and continue with only the next relevant files.
- If the user explicitly requests a larger-context experiment, warn that it may fail and ask before exceeding the 32k budget.
- Never read, write, summarize, or commit secrets and local logs: `gemini_cookies.local.json`, `adapter_env.local.ps1`, `adapter_usage*.jsonl`, `adapter_forwarded_prompt.debug.txt`, `.env*`, or files containing token/password/secret/cookie values.
- For existing files, read the relevant current content first and use `replace_in_file` for localized edits. Use `write_to_file` only for new files or complete small-file rewrites.
- If the user asks to run a command, inspect Git status, or explain code, do not modify files.
- Do not write user instructions, command text, XML tool tags, or surrounding chat text into project files unless the user explicitly says that exact text is desired file content.
- Before `git commit` or `git push`, inspect status and diff summary. Only commit or push when the user explicitly asks for it.
- Ask for confirmation before destructive operations such as deletes, broad moves, `git reset`, or `git checkout --`.
